text.tspan: completed.6.11CARGO OPERATIONSThe Master and deck officers are responsible for the safe loading, storage, carriage and discharge of all cargoes carried on boardships.In order for the Master and deck officers to carry out their responsibilities, guidelines are contained in the Vessel Operations Manual.They shall also abide by any special instructions given by the owners/charterers for the carriage of the cargo.6.12NAVIGATION AND DP OPERATIONSIt is the duty of the Masters of all vessels to ensure, prior to departure from any port, that their ship is in every respect seaworthy, hasappropriate draft and trim and has adequate stability throughout all phases of the intended voyage.The company has in place on all vessels a Vessel Operations Manual in which procedures for various critical aspects for safenavigation and DP Operations are laid down. It shall be the responsibility of the Masters to ensure that such procedures are adheredto by all the navigating officers.The Marine Superintendent/ Sr. Marine Superintendent is responsible for maintaining and improving navigational and DP standardson board the vessels.6.13CONTROL OF OPERATING PROCEDURESThe Technical department supported by other departments keeps an overview of implementation of all operating procedures bothonboard and ashore. The Master is responsible for its compliance onboard his vessel. 6.14CONTROL OF CUSTOMER PROPERTYFor the purpose of this section, “customer” shall not only mean the owners of the vessel, but shall also include the charterers of thevessel. Since the company has assumed responsibility for the technical operation, maintenance and manning of vessels belonging tothe customer, the following may be considered as customer property.Fuel Oil bunkersInstruction Manual and drawings, on board and in the officeCargo securing equipmentCharterers’ and owners’ instructions to the Master Lubricating oilsSpares inventory6.15IDENTIFICATION AND TRACEABILITYA. STORES, SPARES AND REPAIRSAll stores and spares requisitions shall always be documented in the Phoenix System with a reference number with vessel's code foreach requisition. Each requisition can therefore be traced back. All information is archived.Each responsible person for maintenance shall verify following items upon receipt of requisitioned stores, spare parts and lubricatingoils, etc. and during repair work. In case of any deficiencies or problems prompt report should be submitted to the Company giving allrelevant details about stores, spare parts, discrepancy noticed and supplier/ repair contractor for requesting rectification orimprovements. All communications must be routed through Master to Company.Supplies, which are not satisfactory, or do not conform to the specifications as ordered, shall notbe accepted and returned to thesupplier at their cost as far as possible at the port of supply. If for some reasons the same cannot be returned to the supplier at theport of supply, these non-conforming items shall be retained on board, and returned to the supplier from the next convenient port.However if the discrepancy is a minor one or only in terms of quantities, etc., comments on the delivery slip, receipt or workcompletion report shall suffice with signature on it.a) Items are according to requisitions and without problems with type and quality.b) Quantities are as sanctioned and as informed by the Company.c) Items are not contaminated or damagedd) In case of repair work there are no problems with safety management, technical or work completion dates.In order to prevent inadvertent use of the non-conforming item, during the period the same is retained on board, it shall be stowedaway from its normal storing compartment and clearly identified.B. CARGO TRACEABILITYAll operational instructions received from Operators/ Charterers and Charter parties are kept in Voyage Instruction file, to be retainedfor a period of 3 years. All relevant Cargo Papers are retained for 5 years, separate files/ envelopes for each voyage.C. SHIP STATUS IDENTIFICATIONCompany has established and maintains procedures for the identification of ship status at any point in the voyage.It shall be responsibility of Master to ensure that the company’s reporting procedures are strictly adhered to, whereas in the office theresponsibility shall lie with the Technical Superintendent and General Manager.Masters of all vessels are required to forward following routine messages using stipulated formats.7EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS
